Niches, Big and Small
The platonic ideal of reporting =E2=80=93 most closely approximated by news=
papers and TV channels in the Dan Rather era =E2=80=93 saw these mass media=
 companies idealistically delivering fair and unbiased reporting.=C2=A0
The people who ran those media organizations were no more noble than the pe=
ople who run news organizations today. Their incentive was to reach as many=
 people as possible, whatever those people=E2=80=99s beliefs, and the best =
way to do that was to deliver the facts. They were truly mass media.
But, unfortunately, Americans today trust such mass media less than they ev=
er have.=C2=A0
When people look at that chart, they overemphasize the media, believing tha=
t news writers are failing to live up to their old promise of journalistic =
integrity. The real challenge is mass.=C2=A0
The confusing thing is that while many of the same organizations =E2=80=93 =
from The New York Times to NBC =E2=80=93 are still in business, their incen=
tives have changed, and their products have changed alongside their incenti=
ves. They=E2=80=99ve gone from serving the masses, to serving a very large =
niche.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s disconcerting for someone in tech to open up The New York Time=
s and read technology coverage that doesn=E2=80=99t reflect the facts that =
they see on the ground. The fact is, it=E2=80=99s not The New York Times=E2=
=80=99 job to get people to love technology. Their job is to serve their ni=
che.=C2=A0
As Ben Thompson wrote in the excellent Never-Ending Niches [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/9c00fd1f-620b-4942-94f6-8a48c541856d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CWhile quality is r=
elatively binary, the number of ways to be focused =E2=80=94 that is, the n=
umber of niches in the world =E2=80=94 are effectively infinite; success, i=
n other words, is about delivering superior quality in your niche =E2=80=94=
 the former is defined by the latter.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The Times=E2=80=99s niche, he says, includes the =E2=80=9CEverything tech d=
oes is bad=E2=80=9D niche. In that context, even anti-tech stories that are=
 =E2=80=9Cdeeply flawed at best, and willfully mendacious at worst=E2=80=9D=
 are =E2=80=9Cvery high quality for much of The New York Times=E2=80=99s au=
dience.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
This might be a bit controversial to say in tech circles, but that=E2=80=99=
s totally fine! The New York Times is a business, and their readers expect =
something specific from them: dispassionate, measured, =E2=80=9Crealistic=
=E2=80=9D analysis. And, realistically, most founders won=E2=80=99t change =
the world like they all claim they will.
Said differently, the idealistic goal of a publication like The New York Ti=
mes is to verify and contextualize facts about the world. And the truth is =
that in a startup=E2=80=99s earliest days, the facts are sparse and the dre=
am is still, well, a dream.=C2=A0
Mass media journalism and early-stage startups simply don=E2=80=99t have =
=E2=80=9Cmedia-message fit.=E2=80=9D There=E2=80=99s not enough there there=
 to do real journalism on. So either journalists treat startups with the sa=
me tenacity as they=E2=80=99d treat a more mature company and find them lac=
king, or the startup contorts itself into something they think a journalist=
 wants to hear. It=E2=80=99s a mismatch.=C2=A0
But that=E2=80=99s also an opportunity. You don=E2=80=99t win by getting ma=
d, but by competing.=C2=A0
If you view media organizations as businesses with customers, and believe t=
hat the largest underserve important and growing groups of customers, then =
the setup is ripe for disruption.=C2=A0
Disrupting Media
The term disruption is used far too often to mean anything new that compete=
s with anything old, but there=E2=80=99s a specific definition that the lat=
e Harvard professor Clayton Chrisensen used. In What is Disruptive Innovati=
on? [ https://substack.com/redirect/b9db4051-fa8c-4a68-983e-e04adb6170bf?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], he wro=
te (emphasis ours):=C2=A0
First, a quick recap of the idea: =E2=80=9CDisruption=E2=80=9D describes a =
process whereby a smaller company with fewer resources is able to successfu=
lly challenge established incumbent businesses. Specifically, as incumbents=
 focus on improving their products and services for their most demanding (a=
nd usually most profitable) customers, they exceed the needs of some segmen=
ts and ignore the needs of others. Entrants that prove disruptive begin by =
successfully targeting those overlooked segments, gaining a foothold by del=
ivering more-suitable functionality=E2=80=94frequently at a lower price. In=
cumbents, chasing higher profitability in more-demanding segments, tend not=
 to respond vigorously. Entrants then move upmarket, delivering the perform=
ance that incumbents=E2=80=99 mainstream customers require, while preservin=
g the advantages that drove their early success. When mainstream customers =
start adopting the entrants=E2=80=99 offerings in volume, disruption has oc=
curred.=C2=A0
Techno-Optimistic Media serves two overlooked segments: pro-tech audiences =
and founders.=C2=A0
Pro-tech audiences might include people in tech, people who want to work in=
 tech, investors, generally curious people who want to understand where the=
 world is heading, and people who are sick of reading bad news every time t=
hey open the paper. These customers are overlooked by mass media organizati=
ons who are appealing to the broadest common denominator =E2=80=93 who, unf=
ortunately, don=E2=80=99t (yet) love tech.
Techno-Optimistic Media might not do the level of journalism that legacy me=
dia does, and they certainly don=E2=80=99t employ armies of editors and fac=
t-checkers. The product is not as polished. But in exchange, the Techno-Opt=
imistic product is free and, well, optimistic, which means that it is both =
accessible and appealing to pro-tech audiences.=C2=A0
Founders, or more generally subjects of articles, aren=E2=80=99t typically =
thought of as customers of media organizations, but they are, even if they =
don=E2=80=99t pay. When a CEO or politician sits down with a journalist and=
 hands over their message to a third-party, they=E2=80=99re paying with inf=
ormation that would otherwise stay private in exchange for reach and credib=
ility.=C2=A0
Techno-Optimistic Media doesn=E2=80=99t offer founders the reach or general=
 population credibility that an organization like The New York Times does, =
but it does offer founders a way to reach a smaller, more targeted audience=
 with a more direct =E2=80=93 and more predictably favorable =E2=80=93 vers=
ion of their story. In exchange, Techno-Optimistic Media gets access to sto=
ries and insights their pro-tech audiences demand=E2=80=A6 and have a lot o=
f fun producing content about the industries and technologies that they thi=
nk have the greatest chances of changing the world for the better.=C2=A0
If Techno-Optimistic Media displaces any part of legacy media over time, it=
 won=E2=80=99t be by trying to build the same product in a techno-optimisti=
c flavor. It will be by starting at the low-end, and growing alongside the =
founders they partner with.=C2=A0
The Techno-Optimistic Media is explicitly biased and incentive-aligned beca=
use we want tech companies to succeed. We want cheaper energy and abundant =
goods and robot assistants and financial freedom and human flourishing, and=
 our reach will grow as technologists deliver on those promises. And we hav=
e skin in the game, whether as technologists or investors.
Our bias is that technological progress is good, actually.=C2=A0
Creating small spaces for people who share that bias is a surprisingly big =
shift.=C2=A0
Aside: Small Spaces and Scenius
As we transition from =E2=80=9CWhy Techno-Optimistic Media?=E2=80=9D to =E2=
=80=9CHow founders should think about their media strategies,=E2=80=9D a qu=
ick aside on the importance of small spaces and scenes.=C2=A0
Despite everything we=E2=80=99ve written, we understand the temptation to g=
o big. But there=E2=80=99s real value in starting small. It=E2=80=99s true =
in the real world, and we think it=E2=80=99s true online.=C2=A0
In Small Spaces [ https://substack.com/redirect/abc3dbae-aa1e-49ff-a3ec-f77=
93a5ec691?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ], Simon Sarris argues that =E2=80=9Cculture is not created in cities so =
much as assembled and discovered there. It is created in smaller spaces.=E2=
=80=9D
=E2=80=9CGiven the typical assumptions about the multiplicative effects of =
human capital,=E2=80=9D he asks, why has one of these places created four t=
rillion-dollar companies and the other zero?=C2=A0
There are a number of well-studied hypotheses for Palo Alto=E2=80=99s succe=
ss, but Sarris thinks that its smallness is underappreciated.=C2=A0
Why? Sarris has thoughts =E2=80=93 rent prices, remoteness, authenticity, a=
nd the =E2=80=9Cferment that we have relied on in the less-connected world.=
=E2=80=9D Another answer might be purely statistical =E2=80=93 aggregate en=
ough people together, and you=E2=80=99re more likely to end up with an aver=
age group.
But we like Kevin Kelly=E2=80=99s answer best.=C2=A0
In Scenius, or Communal Genius [ https://substack.com/redirect/50412ee7-72e=
d-47df-aab2-e3882653a74c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Kelly examines the factors that contribute to scenius: =
=E2=80=9Cthe intelligence and the intuition of a whole cultural scene. It i=
s the communal form of the concept of the genius.=E2=80=9D
Individuals immersed in a productive scenius will blossom and produce their=
 best work. When buoyed by scenius, you act like genius. Your like-minded p=
eers, and the entire environment inspire you.
If you=E2=80=99ve spent time on tech Twitter or in SF or El Segundo recentl=
y, maybe you=E2=80=99ve felt this. It=E2=80=99s a magical, self-reinforcing=
, self-sustaining loop of attention and motivation.
Kelly believes that four factors are at play:=C2=A0
Mutual appreciation =E2=80=94 Risky moves are applauded by the group, subtl=
ety is appreciated, and friendly competition goads the shy. Scenius can be =
thought of as the best of peer pressure.
Rapid exchange of tools and techniques =E2=80=94 As soon as something is in=
vented, it is flaunted and then shared. Ideas flow quickly because they are=
 flowing inside a common language and sensibility.
Network effects of success =E2=80=94 When a record is broken, a hit happens=
, or breakthrough erupts, the success is claimed by the entire scene. This =
empowers the scene to further success.
Local tolerance for the novelties =E2=80=94 The local =E2=80=9Coutside=E2=
=80=9D does not push back too hard against the transgressions of the scene.=
 The renegades and mavericks are protected by this buffer zone.
Consider these in the context of what we=E2=80=99ve been discussing. All fo=
ur sound more like Techno-Optimistic Media than mass media. Done right, Tec=
hno-Optimistic Media helps cultivate scenius at internet scale: celebration=
 of risky moves, sharing technical ideas in-depth, feeding off of each othe=
r=E2=80=99s success, protecting renegades and mavericks from the outside.=
=C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean ideas are protected from the inside. To the contr=
ary, by creating small spaces and scenes with people who are generally pro-=
technology but have very strong opinions on which technologies get built an=
d how, we can create what Tim Urban calls an Idea Lab [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/2f8d7564-6849-49cc-a315-6fb3ad333203?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
People in the scene can beat the shit out of each other=E2=80=99s ideas, no=
t each other, in the comfy confines of a friendly but opinionated community=
 before they emerge into a broader media landscape that leans Anti-Tech Ech=
o Chamber. As Urban writes,=C2=A0
Ideas in an Idea Lab are treated like hypotheses, which means people are al=
ways looking for opportunities to test what they=E2=80=99ve been thinking a=
bout. Idea Labs are the perfect boxing ring for that testing.
The fact that Techno-Optimistic Media is small, that it doesn=E2=80=99t app=
eal to a mass audience, is a feature, not a bug. Going big =E2=80=93 and di=
luting the audience =E2=80=93 would kill that vibe, and when you strike upo=
n scenius, Kelly says: The best you can do is NOT KILL IT.
You=E2=80=99ll have to go big eventually, if you want to be big, but there=
=E2=80=99s real value in beating up your ideas in small Idea Labs and compe=
titively friendly scenes.=C2=A0
Our advice is not as blunt as =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t work with the mass med=
ia.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s not that simple =E2=80=93 because the mass media =
can actually be extremely good at what they do.=C2=A0
The trick is trying to speak to the right audiences at the right times on t=
he right channels.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s what that looks like in practice.=C2=A0
The Early Days: Go Direct
Startups are an exercise in getting people to believe in a crazy idea, star=
ting with yourself and growing out in concentric circles.=C2=A0
Before there=E2=80=99s even a company, there=E2=80=99s an idea. You can wor=
kshop it, write about it, build prototypes, do market research, and think u=
ntil your brain hurts. The first person your idea needs to survive is you.=
=C2=A0
Once you=E2=80=99ve convinced yourself, you can start to annoy your smartes=
t friends.=C2=A0
Sam D=E2=80=99Amico, founder of Impulse, said in an interview with Jason Ca=
rman [ https://substack.com/redirect/d7b0d6a5-3146-4bfb-8006-a58dfdb94ffe?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
I think a good checkpoint [for whether you=E2=80=99re ready to start a comp=
any] is: =E2=80=98Have you annoyed your friends about this idea enough?=E2=
=80=99 And I definitely did=E2=80=A6 Because if it sticks in your head, and=
 you=E2=80=99re not being dissuaded. San Francisco is an amazing place for =
people who are positive about startup ideas. But if you talk to highly tech=
nical people about stuff like this, they will poke holes in everything. And=
 if you can survive the thunderdome of that, and keep annoying your friends=
 about it, maybe you should consider doing that idea.
