ady to take for a spin outside of the comforts of your local confines.=C2=
=A0
Getting here sequentially means that you=E2=80=99re coming in from a positi=
on of strength, which can be useful whether your first brush with Legacy Me=
dia goes great, or doesn=E2=80=99t. Because it doesn=E2=80=99t always go we=
ll, and it only rarely goes exactly as you planned.=C2=A0
Working with the Legacy Media goes something like this:
Your company does something cool.
You call up your favorite reporters and attempt to convince them that it is=
, indeed, cool.
If they agree, you send them your version of events (a =E2=80=9Cpress relea=
se=E2=80=9D) and any =E2=80=9Cassets=E2=80=9D (videos, photos, etc.) that c=
an accompany it.
[Massive Black Box]
The reporter publishes their story on their own channels.
There are some clear challenges with this model.=C2=A0
First, reporters can, and often do, say no. It=E2=80=99s not their job to r=
eport everything you tell them.=C2=A0
Second, although you can do your best to make your version of events compel=
ling to a reporter, they ultimately decide how to tell your story. They mig=
ht uncover parts of the story that you would like to obscure, or not =E2=80=
=9Cframe=E2=80=9D the story as you would prefer.=C2=A0
Third, you can=E2=80=99t control the timing of a press-driven announcement.=
 The [Massive Black Box] step takes an indeterminate amount of time to clea=
r.=C2=A0
Fourth, the fact that news stories are published on press-owned sites (and =
promoted on press-owned channels) means that you only have intermediate acc=
ess to the folks your news reaches. Viewers on a news site are disproportio=
nately likely to be one-time viewers for you.
If you=E2=80=99ve built up your direct communications and partnered with Te=
chno-Optimistic Media, however, a lot of these challenges disappear.=C2=A0
If the story is great, you can share it with thousands of people who have b=
een there throughout the journey and will be pumped to see your name in lig=
hts. They=E2=80=99ll feel proud and validated in their early belief, and sh=
are the story with their own audiences.=C2=A0
If it goes poorly, you=E2=80=99ve bought insurance.=C2=A0
