argin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Disrupting Media</stro=
ng></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The term disruption is used far too often t=
o mean anything new that competes with anything old, but there&#8217;s a sp=
ecific definition that the late Harvard professor Clayton Chrisensen used. =
In </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/b9db4051-fa8c-4a68-9=
83e-e04adb6170bf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;"=
>What is Disruptive Innovation?</a></em><span>, he wrote (emphasis ours):&#=
160;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin:=
 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>First,=
 a quick recap of the idea: &#8220;Disruption&#8221; describes a process wh=
ereby a </span><strong>smaller company with fewer resources</strong><span> =
is able to </span><strong>successfully challenge established incumbent busi=
nesses</strong><span>. Specifically, as incumbents </span><strong>focus on =
improving their products and services for their most demanding (and usually=
 most profitable) customers</strong><span>, they </span><strong>exceed the =
needs of some segments and ignore the needs of others</strong><span>. Entra=
nts that prove disruptive </span><strong>begin by successfully targeting th=
ose overlooked segments</strong><span>, gaining a foothold by </span><stron=
g>delivering more-suitable functionality</strong><span>&#8212;</span><stron=
g>frequently at a lower price</strong><span>. Incumbents, chasing higher pr=
ofitability in more-demanding segments, tend not to respond vigorously. </s=
pan><strong>Entrants then move upmarket</strong><span>, delivering the perf=
ormance that incumbents&#8217; mainstream customers require, </span><strong=
>while preserving the advantages that drove their early success</strong><sp=
an>. </span><strong>When mainstream customers start adopting the entrants&#=
8217; offerings in volume, disruption has occurred.</strong></em><span>&#16=
0;</span></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Techno-Optimistic Media s=
erves two overlooked segments: </span><strong>pro-tech audiences</strong><s=
pan> and </span><strong>founders</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><strong>Pro-tech audiences</strong><span> might include people in=
 tech, people who want to work in tech, investors, generally curious people=
 who want to understand where the world is heading, and people who are sick=
 of reading bad news every time they open the paper. These customers are ov=
erlooked by mass media organizations who are appealing to the broadest comm=
on denominator &#8211; who, unfortunately, don&#8217;t (yet) love tech.</sp=
an></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Techno-Optimistic Media might not do the level of =
journalism that legacy media does, and they certainly don&#8217;t employ ar=
mies of editors and fact-checkers. The product is not as polished. But in e=
xchange, the Techno-Optimistic product is free and, well, optimistic, which=
 means that it is both accessible and appealing to pro-tech audiences.&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Founders</strong><span>, or more generally s=
ubjects of articles, aren&#8217;t typically thought of as customers of medi=
a organizations, but they are, even if they don&#8217;t pay. When a CEO or =
politician sits down with a journalist and hands over their message to a th=
ird-party, they&#8217;re paying with information that would otherwise stay =
private in exchange for reach and credibility.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><span>Techno-Optimistic Media doesn&#8217;t offer founders the reach =
or general population credibility that an organization like </span><em>The =
New York Times</em><span> does, but it does offer founders a way to reach a=
 smaller, more targeted audience with a more direct &#8211; and more predic=
tably favorable &#8211; version of their story. In exchange, Techno-Optimis=
tic Media gets access to stories and insights their pro-tech audiences dema=
nd&#8230; and have a lot of fun producing content about the industries and =
technologies that they think have the greatest chances of changing the worl=
d for the better.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If Techno-Optimistic Me=
dia displaces any part of legacy media over time, it won&#8217;t be by tryi=
ng to build the same product in a techno-optimistic flavor. It will be by s=
tarting at the low-end, and growing alongside the founders they partner wit=
h.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The Techno-Optimistic Media is explicitly bia=
sed and incentive-aligned because we want tech companies to succeed. We wan=
t cheaper energy and abundant goods and robot assistants and financial free=
dom and human flourishing, and our reach will grow as technologists deliver=
 on those promises. And we have skin in the game, whether as technologists =
or investors.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Our bias is that technological p=
rogress is good, actually</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>Creating small spaces for people who share that bias is a surprisingly big=
 shift.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appe=
arance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-a=
