e-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><em><strong=
>Aside: </strong></em><strong>Small Spaces and Scenius</strong></h3><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">As we transition from &#8220;Why Techno-Optimistic Media?&#8221;=
 to &#8220;How founders should think about their media strategies,&#8221; a=
 quick aside on the importance of small spaces and scenes.&#160;</p><p styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;">Despite everything we&#8217;ve written, we understand the tempta=
tion to go big. But there&#8217;s real value in starting small. It&#8217;s =
true in the real world, and we think it&#8217;s true online.&#160;</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;"><span>In </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/a=
bc3dbae-aa1e-49ff-a3ec-f7793a5ec691?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-deco=
ration: underline;">Small Spaces</a></em><span>, Simon Sarris argues that &=
#8220;culture is not created in cities so much as assembled and discovered =
there. </span><strong>It is created in smaller spaces.</strong><span>&#8221=
;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;Given the typical assumptions about th=
